r, Ehrhardt, Erwin, Gunther.","German (mainly <b>Günther</b>): variant of   Gunter  ."]},{"name":"Goenner","meanings":["North German (<b>Gönner</b>): from the personal name <i>Gönner</i>, a variant of   Gunter  , composed of the elements <i>gund</i> ‘battle’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’. Compare   Gonnerman  ."]},{"name":"Gunder","meanings":["German (also <b>Günder</b>): variant of   Gunter  ."]},{"name":"Guenter","meanings":["German (mainly <b>Günter</b>): see   Gunter  ."]}]},{"name":"Janet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a diminutive of   Jane  , already in common use in the Middle English period. It remained in use in Scotland and in some parts of England well into the 17th century and was revived at the end of the 19th century to much more widespread use, while still retaining its popularity in Scotland. Since the 1960s, however, it has rather gone out of fashion in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Jannet","meanings":["Originally a diminutive of   Jane  , already in common use in the Middle English period. It remained in use in Scotland and in some parts of England well into the 17th century and was revived at the end of the 19th century to much more widespread use, while still retaining its popularity in Scotland. Since the 1960s, however, it has rather gone out of fashion in Britain."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Janet Gunter was born about 1090, in Wales, her father, Sir William Gunter, was 23 and her mother, Jannet Bois, was 21. She married John Burghill about 1107, in Burghill, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1090–":"umbes 1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1095–Female":"1095–Surnud","1098–Male":"1098–Surnud","1090–1135":"1090–1135","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1069–1100":"1069–1100","1071–Female":"1071–Surnud","1090":"1090","about 1095":"umbes 1095","about 1090":"umbes 1090","